04224nam a22006135i 9780292754508DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212014txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927545087 a10.7560/7540412doi  a(DE-B1597)587580  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aN8217.A94bT47 2014eb 7aART0151102bisacsh04a743/.896292222231 aTerranova, Charissa N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAutomotive Prosthetic :bTechnological Mediation and the Car in Conceptual Art /cCharissa N. Terranova. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Conceptual Car Art: Rethinking Conceptualism through Technology -- tChapter 2. Mobile Perception and the Automotive Prosthetic: Photoconceptualism, the Car, and Urban Space -- tChapter 3. The Nows of the Automotive Prosthetic: Moving Images, Time, and the Car -- tChapter 4. Communication Space: Automotive Urbanism in Dan Graham’s Work -- tChapter 5. Hummer: The Cultural Militarism of Art Based on the SUV -- tChapter 6. Richard Prince: The Fetish and Automotive Maleficium -- tConclusion The “Freedom” of Automotive Existence -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the twenty-first century, we are continually confronted with the existential side of technology—the relationships between identity and the mechanizations that have become extensions of the self. Focusing on one of humanity’s most ubiquitous machines, Automotive Prosthetic: Technological Mediation and the Car in Conceptual Art combines critical theory and new media theory to form the first philosophical analysis of the car within works of conceptual art. These works are broadly defined to encompass a wide range of creative expressions, particularly in car-based conceptual art by both older, established artists and younger, emerging artists, including Ed Ruscha, Martha Rosler, Richard Prince, Sylvie Fleury, Yael Bartana, Jeremy Deller, and Jonathan Schipper. At its core, the book offers an alternative formation of conceptual art understood according to technology, the body moving through space, and what art historian, curator, and artist Jack Burnham calls “relations.” This thought-provoking study illuminates the ways in which the automobile becomes a naturalized extension of the human body, incarnating new forms of “car art” and spurring a technological reframing of conceptual art. Steeped in a sophisticated take on the image and semiotics of the car, the chapters probe the politics of materialism as well as high/low debates about taste, culture, and art. The result is a highly innovative approach to contemporary intersections of art and technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAutomobiles in art. 0aConceptual artxThemes, motives. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292754508423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292754508/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK